Interview Questions

Q1. What is SortedSet in Java?
-->SortedSet is an interface that extends the Set interface and stores unique elements in sorted (ascending) order.

      The elements are sorted:
      
      By their natural ordering, or
      By a Comparator provided during creation.
      
      The most common implementation is TreeSet.




Q2. Which class commonly implements SortedSet?
-->The most commonly used implementation of SortedSet is TreeSet.
      
      Characteristics of TreeSet
      Maintains sorted order.
      Does not allow duplicate elements.
      Does not allow null values.
      Internally uses a Red-Black Tree.
      
      Example:
      
      SortedSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();
      
      set.add(30);
      set.add(10);
      set.add(20);
      
      System.out.println(set);
      
      Output
      
      [10, 20, 30]



Q3. Can SortedSet store null values? Why or why not?
-->No.

      A SortedSet (typically implemented by TreeSet) does not allow null values.
      
      Reason
      
      TreeSet compares elements to maintain sorted order. Comparing null with other elements causes a NullPointerException.
      
      Example:
      
      SortedSet<String> set = new TreeSet<>();
      
      set.add(null);
      
      Output
      
      Exception in thread "main"
      java.lang.NullPointerException



Q4. What methods are introduced in SortedSet that are not in Set?
-->SortedSet introduces several methods for working with sorted elements.
| Method                               | Description                                                                     |
| ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `first()`                            | Returns the first (lowest) element.                                             |
| `last()`                             | Returns the last (highest) element.                                             |
| `headSet(E toElement)`               | Returns elements less than the given element.                                   |
| `tailSet(E fromElement)`             | Returns elements greater than or equal to the given element.                    |
| `subSet(E fromElement, E toElement)` | Returns elements within the specified range.                                    |
| `comparator()`                       | Returns the comparator used for sorting, or `null` if natural ordering is used. |

Interview Tip
HashSet → Unique elements, no insertion order, backed by HashMap.
LinkedHashSet → Unique elements, maintains insertion order, backed by LinkedHashMap.
SortedSet (TreeSet) → Unique elements, sorted order, backed by a Red-Black Tree, does not allow null values.
